assets.headline: Ageing poorly? Perhaps you are 'rusting' from too much iron in your system
assets.indexHeadline: When iron goes rogue in the body
assets.theAbstract: Researchers have found that many people who are ageing poorly are "rusting" from too much iron in their system.

relatedImages.description: Researchers have found that many people who are ageing poorly are "rusting" from too much iron in their system.
Treatment is simple. It requires people to be bled so they shed some iron-rich blood and clear their iron overload.
Professor David Melzer says the early signs of haemochromatosis are difficult for doctors to spot and sometimes misdiagnosed.

Emeritus Professor Lawrie Powell's real concern is for younger people, in their 40s and 50s, who have not been diagnosed and then develop complications including cirrhosis of the liver and liver cancer.
A standard blood test does not include anything to raise the suspicion a person has iron overload disease.
One way to age successfully is to maintain normal iron level  and reduce the likelihood of rusting up.
If you know this hereditary disease is in your family, you can be alert for it. But ironically, because it is largely undiagnosed, that can be hard to know.
Many people have one copy of the faulty gene but the disease usually manifests only if a person has two copies.
Although more common in men, women can be severely affected by haemochromatosis too.
Menstruation affords women some protection against iron overload, but this ends with menopause.
